# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] The **1927 World Series** was the championship series in Major League Baseball for the 1927 season.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] The 24th edition of the World Series, it was a best-of-seven playoff that pitted the American League (AL) champion New York Yankees against the National League (NL) champion Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] This was the first sweep of a National League team by an American League team.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] This was the first World Series matchup between the Pirates and Yankees.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] The 1927 Yankees led the American League in runs scored, hits, triples, home runs, base on balls, batting average, slugging average and on-base percentage.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] It featured legends Babe Ruth and Lou Gehrig at their peaks.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] The team won a then-league record 110 games, finished with a 19-game lead over the second place Philadelphia Athletics, and are considered by many to be the greatest team in the history of baseball.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] The 1927 Pittsburgh Pirates, with MVP Paul Waner, led the National League in runs, hits, batting average and on-base percentage.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] The 1927 New York Yankees had perhaps the most feared line-up in the history of baseball.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Nicknamed "Murderers Row," with Babe Ruth at the peak of his considerable powers, hitting .356 with a then-record 60 home runs and 164 RBI that year.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] He was complemented by future Hall of Famers Lou Gehrig at first base, who hit .373 with 47 home runs and a league-leading 175 RBI, Tony Lazzeri at second base who drove in 102 runs with a .309 average, and center fielder Earle Combs, who hit .356 and scored 137 runs as the team's leadoff hitter.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Left fielder Bob Meusel also drove in over 100 runs, with a .337 average.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] The team's pitching staff was led by another Hall of Famer, Waite Hoyt, who had his best season with a 22–7 record and a league-leading 2.63 ERA to add to his league-leading wins total.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Moore would have won the ERA title under current rules, but in those days qualification was based on the number of complete games pitched, and he made only 12 starts all year: 13 of his wins and a league-leading 13 saves (figured retroactively) came during his 38 relief appearances.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Rounding out the staff were veteran Dutch Ruether (13–6, 3.38), George Pipgras (10–3, 4.11) and swingman Myles Thomas (7–4, 4.87).
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] To no one's surprise, the Yankees ran away with the pennant under the leadership of manager Miller Huggins.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] They finished with a record of 110–44, 19 games in front of the second-place Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] They were overwhelming favorites to win the World Series.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] The 1927 Pittsburgh Pirates were by no means a weak team, but they certainly suffer in comparison with their American League rivals.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] The Pirates went 94–60 for manager Donie Bush during the regular season, finishing 1+1⁄2 games ahead of the defending World Champions St.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] The Pirates also had their share of future Hall of Famers, but they were not quite of the caliber of those of the Yankees.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] The team's best hitter was right fielder Paul "Big Poison" Waner, who hit a league-leading .380 and drove in 131 runs, also a league-leading total, and hit a team high 9 home runs.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] His brother, rookie center fielder Lloyd "Little Poison" Waner hit .355 and scored a league-leading 133 runs, in spite of his almost complete lack of power (he collected just 25 extra-base hits in over 650 plate appearances).
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Third baseman Pie Traynor hit .342 and drove in over 100 runs, joining shortstop Glenn Wright who also topped the century mark and like Paul also hit 9 home runs.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] However, Wright and Paul Waner also led the team in home runs with 9 each, underscoring the huge difference in power with their rivals: the Pirates hit 54 home runs as a team, fewer than Babe Ruth by himself, and barely a third as many as the Yankees' 158.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Other solid hitters for the Pirates included first baseman Joe Harris, who hit .326 with 73 RBI, second baseman George Grantham (.305) and left fielder Clyde Barnhart (.319).
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] In fact, catcher Johnny Gooch, who hit .258, was the only regular besides Wright to hit below .300, and back-up outfielder Kiki Cuyler added his own .309 average in 285 at-bats to the parade, as the Pirates batted .305 as a team—pitchers included.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] The Pirates' pitching was not as dominant.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Two veterans of the 1925 World Championship team, Lee Meadows and Ray Kremer both posted 19 wins, with Kremer leading the league with a 2.47 ERA.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Carmen Hill had pitched part of six seasons in the majors before 1927, never winning more than three games.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] In 1927, he put everything together, winning a team-leading 22 games against 11 losses, with a 3.24 ERA at age 31.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Vic Aldridge went 15–10 as the fourth starter, but his 4.25 ERA was well over the league average.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] In the bullpen, Johnny Miljus put together a good season, posting a 1.90 ERA in 76 innings, with an 8–3 record.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] The 1927 World Series opened under sunny skies and balmy weather at Forbes Field in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, on Wednesday, October 5.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] The crowd of 41,467 saw Yankee right-hander Waite Hoyt (22–6, 2.64 ERA) and Pirate ace Ray Kremer (19–8, 2.47 ERA) oppose each other in Game 1.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Fisher was at Forbes Field, as well as New York City Mayor Jimmy Walker.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Commissioner Kenesaw Mountain Landis was seated near the Yankees' dugout.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Adding to the festivities was a brass band in red coats that paraded around the field before the game.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] The photographers took pictures of Pirates' Manager Donie Bush and the Yankees' Miller Huggins shaking hands.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] The Babe was photographed with Huggins, Bush, Mayor Walker, Lou Gehrig, and the Waners.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] When the game started, Earle Combs hit the first ball Kremer threw and drove it deep to left field, where Clyde Barnhart caught it.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] After Mark Koenig struck out swinging, Babe Ruth came up.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] He swung at the first ball and singled to right field for the first hit of the series.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Then on a count of three and two, Gehrig hit a short fly to right field.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Paul Waner tried to make a shoestring catch, but the ball got through him for a triple and Ruth scored.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] In the bottom of the first, the Pirates tied the game at one.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Lloyd Waner was hit by a pitch, moved to third on his brother's double, and tagged up on Glenn Wright's sacrifice fly.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] With one out in the third, second baseman George Grantham kicked Koenig's grounder behind first base for an error.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Ruth again hit Kremer's first pitch and smashed a single to right, sending Koenig to third.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] With the bases loaded, Kremer walked Bob Meusel, forcing home Koenig.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Tony Lazzeri then grounded to Wright, who got the ball to second in time to force Meusel, but Grantham could not get rid of it in time to complete a double play.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] With Gehrig on third and Lazzeri on first, a double steal was attempted.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Catcher Earl Smith made a bluff throw to second and then threw to Pie Traynor at third, catching Gehrig halfway between the bases, but Smith let Traynor's return throw to the plate get past him for an error.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] The Pirates picked up one run in the bottom of the third on Kremer's double and Paul Waner's single, making the score 4–2.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] After Hoyt developed a blister on a finger of his pitching hand in the fourth, Huggins watched him carefully.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Koenig doubled to center in the fifth and went to third when Ruth grounded out to Grantham.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Gehrig's sacrifice fly to Paul Waner scored Koenig.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] The Pirates came back with one run in the bottom of the inning on Lloyd Waner's double and Barnhart's single to left.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] After Lazzeri doubled in the sixth, Pirates Manager Donie Bush lifted Kremer and brought in right-hander Johnny Miljus, who retired the side.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Pittsburgh came up in the eighth trailing 5–3.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Wright lined a single over Lazzeri's head.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Huggins decided that Hoyt had had enough and called for Wilcy Moore.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Grantham grounded to Gehrig who threw to Koenig in time to force Traynor at second.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] On the play, Koenig was bowled over and had the air knocked out of him.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Wright went to third on the play and scored on Joe Harris's single to center, making the score 5–4.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] On a daring run and long slide, Grantham beat Combs's throw to third.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Smith then grounded to Gehrig, who stepped on first to end the inning.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Moore retired the Pirates in order in the ninth.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] The Yankees won Game 1 of the World Series, 5–4.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] The Pirates opened the scoring in the bottom of the first.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Lloyd Waner tripled down the left field foul line, and Clyde Barnhart drove Ruth up against the concrete wall in right on his sacrifice fly scoring Waner.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] In the top of the third, Combs singled between Harris and Grantham and raced to third on Koenig's line single over second, scoring on Lloyd Waner's fumble sending Koenig around to third.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Ruth's high sacrifice fly to Lloyd Waner scored Koenig.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Gehrig doubled to the exit gate in right-center.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Wright then made an acrobatic diving stop of Meusel's drive headed for left field but couldn't regain his balance in time to throw Meusel out, Gehrig reaching third base and scoring on Lazzeri's sacrifice fly to Paul Waner.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Pipgras pitched beautifully, with a blazing fastball and a sharp-breaking curve, scattering six hits over seven innings.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] In the top of the eighth, Meusel singled over second.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] On a hit-and-run play, Lazzeri singled to right, Meusel racing to third.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] When Aldridge's wild pitch almost knocked Dugan down, Meusel scored and Lazzeri went to second.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Dugan attempted a sacrifice bunt, but catcher Johnny Gooch pounced on the ball and threw to third base to get Lazzeri sliding in.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Aldridge then walked Benny Bengough and Pipgras, and southpaw Mike Cvengros relieved him.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] He hit Combs forcing in Dugan, and gave up a single to Koenig scoring Bengough.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] The Yankees led 6–1, and held on to win 6–2.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] The Series moved to New York for Game 3 without a travel day off.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Starter Herb Pennock retired leadoff hitter Lloyd Waner on an easy roller to Koenig.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Rhyne and Paul Waner both flied to Meusel in left.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] With the Yankees up in the first, on a count of two and two, leadoff hitter Combs slapped a single over second.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Koenig got an infield hit on a ground ball that bounced off starter Lee Meadows' glove and was kicked around by Rhyne, Combs reaching second.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] After Ruth popped to Wright behind second, Gehrig got hold of a fastball and drove it to the warning track in left-center for a triple scoring both Combs and Koenig, but was thrown out at the plate trying for an inside-the-park home run.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] The Yankees led 2–0 giving Pennock all the runs he needed.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] He retired the Pirates in order without a hit over the first seven innings.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Lazzeri opened the home half of the seventh with a single into short center, only the fifth hit of the game, all by the Yanks.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Dugan bunted him to second and beat the throw to first.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Huggins sent up Cedric Durst to bat for Grabowski.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] His grounder moved Lazzeri to third and Dugan to second.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Rhyne fielded Pennock's slow grounder but threw to the plate too late to get Lazzeri, Dugan taking third and Pennock reaching first.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Koenig's deep double to right wall scored Pennock and put Combs on third.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Lefthander Mike Cvengros relieved Meadows, but Ruth crushed a home run high into the right-field bleachers, the crowd cheering wildly as he trotted around the bases behind Combs and Koenig.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] The inning finally ended when Cvengros struck out Gehrig and Meusel.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] The Yankees led 8–0, and held on for an 8–1 win.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Pennock finished with a three-hitter, walking none.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Looking to become the manager of the first American League club to sweep a World Series in four straight games, Huggins sent Wilcy Moore to the mound against the Pirates' Carmen Hill for Game 4.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Lloyd Waner led off the game with a drive off Moore's glove and beat it out for a hit.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Koenig threw out Barnhart, sending Little Poison to second.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] The Yanks tied the game at one in the bottom of the first when the first three hitters, Combs, Koenig and Ruth, all singled to right.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] In the bottom of the fifth inning, Combs singled to short center.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Koenig struck out swinging but Ruth hit his second home run of the Series, to deep center.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] In the top of the seventh inning, Smith would have grounded out third to first base, but Moore dropped Gehrig's toss for an error.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Pitcher Emil Yde ran for Smith, and Fred Brickell batted for Hill.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Lazzeri, in his haste to make a double play on Brickell's grounder, bobbled the ball and both runners reached, Yde taking second and Brickell making it to first.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Lloyd Waner's sacrifice bunt moved them up.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Barnhart's single over second scored Yde and sent Brickell to third.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Paul Waner's sacrifice fly to center scored Brickell, tying the score at three apiece.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] There was a new battery for the Pirates in the bottom of the seventh, Johnny Miljus and catcher Johnny Gooch.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] The score remained tied through the seventh, the eighth and the top of the ninth, bringing the Yanks up in their half of the ninth with a chance to win the game and the series.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Koenig beat out a bunt down the third base line for a single, bringing Ruth up.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Miljus' wild pitch sent Combs to third and Koenig to second, and manager Bush ordered Miljus to walk Ruth, loading the bases for Gehrig, who struck out swinging as did Meusel looking.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Lazzeri fouled deep into the left field bleachers for strike one, but on the next pitch Miljus uncorked another wild pitch.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Combs raced home with the winning run, and the Series was over with the Yankees winning 4–3.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] To date, this is the only World Series to end with a runner scoring on a wild pitch.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] The Yankees would go on to repeat as World Series champions the next year, sweeping the St.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] Louis Cardinals to become the first team to pull off back-to-back sweeps in the World Series.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1927-world-series] The Pirates and Yankees would meet again in the World Series in 1960, where the Pirates returned the favor and defeated the Yankees in seven games after being six outs away from elimination in Game 7.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] The **1928 World Series** was the championship series in Major League Baseball for the 1928 season.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] The 25th edition of the World Series, it was a best-of-seven playoff that matched the American League (AL) champion New York Yankees versus the National League (NL) champion St.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] The Yankees beat the Cardinals in four games to win their third championship and become the first team to do back-to-back sweeps.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] Babe Ruth hit .625 (10 for 16) as the Yankees outscored their opponents by a combined score of 27–10.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] As he had done against the Cards in the 1926 Series, Ruth hit three home runs over the right field pavilion in Sportsman's Park in Game 4, the only player to do it in two different World Series through the 2016 season.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] Unlike 1926, however, it occurred in the final game of a Series won by the Yanks and finished off their two consecutive World Series sweeps.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] Lou Gehrig also had a good Series, hitting .545 (6 for 11) with four home runs.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] He drove in as many runs by himself (9) as the entire Cardinal team combined.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] His OPS of 2.433 is, through 2024, the highest World Series OPS of all time.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] Bill McKechnie became the second manager to lead two different teams to the World Series, and like Pat Moran before him, won one and lost one.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] In a fashion similar to 1926, Bill Sherdel took the mound in Game 1 for the Cardinals.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] Ruth doubled with 2 outs in the first inning.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] Ruth lashed another double in the fourth and scored ahead of Bob Meusel's home run, one of only four hits off Sherdel in his seven innings.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] Consecutive singles by Mark Koenig, Ruth and Gehrig-for his second RBI-against Cards reliever Syl Johnson gave the Yankees the 4th run and a 1–0 series lead.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] The Cardinals produced 30 percent (3) of their runs in the Series in the second inning of game 2.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] George Harper walked, Jimmie Wilson doubled, Rabbit Maranville singled, and Grover Cleveland Alexander reached on second baseman Tony Lazzeri's errant throw.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] After that, George Pipgras allowed only two more Cardinal hits, walking 3 other St.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] Miller Huggins had helped him straighten out a delivery problem.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] Pipgras consistently struck out the Cardinals with his curveballs, and they didn't score again.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] New York went ahead 4–3 in the bottom of the second inning off Alexander, who did not do well after that.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] Gehrig, having homered earlier (in the first inning to give the Yankees a 3–0 lead), drew a walk, and Meusel drove in a run with a double.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] A hit batsman and another run-scoring hit gave the Yankees a 4-run lead, and that was how it ended.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] The Redbirds, as the Cardinals were affectionately called by fans, led only 3 times the entire series and held an advantage in this game for 3 innings, the longest span in the series.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] They put up a 2–0 score in the 1st inning on singles by Andy High and Frankie Frisch, followed by a line drive that center fielder Cedric Durst couldn't catch, giving Jim Bottomley a 2-run double.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] Louis run came in the 5th inning, when Taylor Douthit was hit by a pitch and scored to make it a 3–3 game on High's double.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] Where the Cardinals had to scrape together runs, the Yankees did not.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] Gehrig homered into the right-field pavilion.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] In the fourth inning, Ruth laced a single and Gehrig followed with a hard line drive that skipped over the head of charging fielder Douthit.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] The ball rolled to the fence, and Gehrig went around the bases for a two-run inside-the-park homer.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] Ruth took to the bases again in the sixth inning when his grounder forced out Koenig.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] 3rd baseman High fielded Meusel's bouncer and tried to start a double play.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] His throw got Gehrig at second, but Frisch's relay went wild and rolled to the fence.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] As Bottomley scampered after the ball, Ruth rounded third base and headed for home.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] The throw beat him, and umpire Bill McGowan called him out, but the impact from Ruth's hit in the collision jarred the ball loose from catcher Jimmie Wilson, and McGowan changed the call.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] Later in the inning, Meusel scored on a double steal.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] The Yankees scored another run that inning to make it 6–3.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] Another run in the seventh was their last of the game, making it 7-3.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] After Game 3, Cardinals manager Bill McKechnie was still hopeful, despite losing 3 games in a row.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] "It[sic] they can win three games, so can we.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] And this thing isn't over until the fourth game is won," he was quoted as saying.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] The Cards led 2–1 in the top of the seventh.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] 21-game-winning southpaw Will Sherdel had an 0–2 count on Babe Ruth, who turned to say something to catcher Earl Smith.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] Seizing what he thought was a great opportunity to end the at-bat, Sherdel "quick-pitched", or threw without a windup, for what he thought was strike three on the Babe.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] "Quick pitches" were legal in the National League, but not in the American League or the World Series.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] So NL plate umpire Cy Pfirman called "no pitch", causing a vociferous argument with the Cardinals.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] Ruth then took two balls to even the count at 2–2 before homering to tie the game at two apiece.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] Gehrig's ensuing back-to-back home run, his fourth of the Series, gave the Yanks a lead they never relinquished.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] They scored twice more in the seventh, and Ruth finished the inning off with his third homer of the game in the two-run Yankee eighth.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] Louis scored a lone run in the bottom of the ninth to make it 7–3, but that was their last, as future Hall of Famer Frankie Frisch hit a left field foul fly caught on the run by none other than the Babe Ruth up against the stands, as angry Cardinal fans swatted him with newspapers and programs.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] But Ruth merely kept running right into the dugout, holding the ball in the air and giving the Yankees their second straight World Series sweep.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] In 1930, Ruth called this game the biggest thrill of his career.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] Since 1922, World Series games were broadcast by radio.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1928-world-series] The announcers for this years Series were Graham McNamee and Phillips Carlin for NBC's radio network.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1929-world-series] The **1929 World Series** was the championship series of Major League Baseball for the 1929 season.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1929-world-series] The 26th edition of the World Series, it was a best-of-seven playoff that pitted the American League (AL) champion Philadelphia Athletics against the National League (NL) champion Chicago Cubs.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1929-world-series] The Athletics defeated the Cubs in five games to win the Series.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1929-world-series] This was the first World Series game ever played at Wrigley Field.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1929-world-series] Because seven of the eight regulars in the Cubs' lineup hit right-handed, Athletics manager Connie Mack started only right-handed pitchers during the series and kept all his left-handed pitchers in the bullpen, even though two of his best starters, Lefty Grove and Rube Walberg, were left-handed.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1929-world-series] The Athletics' Howard Ehmke, who started his major league career in 1915, had been a good starting pitcher, but by 1929, he was suffering from a sore arm.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1929-world-series] Pitching only occasionally, he finished the regular season with a 7–2 record, a 3.29 earned run average, and 20 strikeouts in 54.2 innings.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1929-world-series] Meanwhile, the Athletics had a big lead in the AL standings.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1929-world-series] In August, Mack told Ehmke that he was going to be released after the season.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1929-world-series] Ehmke accepted the decision but said that he would like to pitch in a World Series game, having never done so before.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1929-world-series] In mid-September, with both league pennant races wrapped up, Mack had Ehmke leave the team and go on the road to scout the NL champion Cubs for the last few weeks of the season, telling him to be prepared to start game 1 of the World Series.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1929-world-series] Mack kept the pitching decision a secret until the day of the game.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1929-world-series] The Athletics had plenty of good pitchers available, and players on both teams were surprised that Ehmke was starting.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1929-world-series] However, with his knowledge of the Cubs' batters and a rested arm, Ehmke pitched a complete game, winning 3–1 with no earned runs allowed and 13 strikeouts.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1929-world-series] The strikeout total broke the World Series record that had been set by Ed Walsh in 1906; Ehmke's record then stood until it was broken by Carl Erskine in 1953.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1929-world-series] This ended up being the last win of Ehmke's career and also became one of the most famous games in baseball history.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1929-world-series] Attending the game was nine-year-old John Paul Stevens, who would grow up to become a Supreme Court Justice.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1929-world-series] Behind the pitching of George Earnshaw and Grove, the Athletics won 9–3 and took a 2–0 lead in the series.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1929-world-series] Jimmie Foxx became the first player to homer in his first two World Series games.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1929-world-series] Al Simmons also homered and had four runs batted in.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1929-world-series] Game 3 was a pitchers' duel that featured many tense moments.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1929-world-series] Guy Bush won this game for the Cubs' only victory, holding the Athletics to one run despite allowing nine hits and two walks.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1929-world-series] Earnshaw started his second straight game for the Athletics and allowed only one earned run himself.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1929-world-series] Sticking to his right-handed-pitchers-only policy, Mack again made a risky move in Game 4 by starting 46-year-old Jack Quinn.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1929-world-series] Unlike Ehmke, however, Quinn was no challenge to the Cubs' hitters, who scored seven runs off him before Mack pulled him in the sixth inning.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1929-world-series] Trailing 8–0, the Athletics then scored 10 runs in the bottom of the seventh inning and won the game.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1929-world-series] In the middle of the rally that became known as the "Mack Attack", Cubs center fielder Hack Wilson lost Mule Haas's fly ball in the sun, and Haas circled the bases for a three-run inside-the-park home run, bringing the Athletics to within a run at 8–7.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1929-world-series] This was the last inside-the-park home run in a World Series game until Game 1 of the 2015 World Series.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1929-world-series] The eight-run deficit overcome by the Athletics is still the largest in postseason history.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1929-world-series] Art Nehf's relief pitching appearance in this game was his last in the major leagues.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1929-world-series] Mack gave Ehmke his second start of the Series, but without the advantage of surprise, he was less effective, touched for two runs, and taken out in the fourth inning.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1929-world-series] The Athletics trailed 2–0 going into the bottom of the ninth.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1929-world-series] However, Haas tied the game up with a two-run homer.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1929-world-series] Then, after a double by Simmons and an intentional walk to Foxx, Bing Miller's double scored Simmons to give the Athletics their first World Series championship in 16 years.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] The **1930 World Series** was the championship series of Major League Baseball for the 1930 season.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] The 27th edition of the World Series, it was a best-of-seven playoff that pitted the American League (AL) champion (and defending World Series champion) Philadelphia Athletics against the National League (NL) champion St.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] The Athletics defeated the Cardinals in six games to win their fifth championship.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] Philadelphia's pitching ace Lefty Grove, and George Earnshaw, the No.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] 2 man in Mack's rotation, won two games apiece.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] Earnshaw also pitched seven scoreless innings as the Game 5 starter, but ended up with a no-decision as Grove relieved him in the eighth and took the win on Jimmie Foxx's two-run homer in the top of the ninth for the game's only scoring.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] The Cardinals led the National League in runs scored and averaged six runs per game in the regular season, but could manage only two runs per game in this World Series.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] Their win this year tied them with the Boston Red Sox for most World Series wins as of that point (five) until 1937, when the New York Yankees surged ahead of both in World Series wins and have gone on to amass 27 World Series championships as of 2026.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] The city of Philadelphia would have to wait 50 years until its next World Series championship, when the Phillies became the last of the "Original Sixteen" MLB franchises to win a World Series.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] This World Series also marks the beginning of the Cardinals run of dominance in the National League in the early 1930s.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] They would win the pennant three times between 1930 and 1934 and the World Series in 1931 and '34.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] This would also be the final World Series where both teams uniforms did not have numbers.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] The A's managed only five hits off of Grimes in Game 1, but all were for extra bases and each produced a run in five different innings.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] Al Simmons and Mickey Cochrane hit solo home runs for the A's, helping Lefty Grove to a 5–2 win.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] The A's struck first in the bottom of the second when Jimmie Foxx tripled and scored on Bing Miller's sacrifice fly.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] The Cardinals loaded the bases in the third on three straight leadoff singles, then Taylor Douthit's lineout and Sparky Adams's sacrifice fly scored a run each.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] Simmons's home run in the fourth tied the game.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] In the sixth, Max Bishop walked with one out and scored on Jimmy Dykes' double.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] Next inning, Mule Haas tripled with one out and scored on Joe Boley's groundout.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] Cochrane's eighth inning home run gave the A's their last run of the game.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] George Earnshaw allowed six hits and walked one, putting the A's ahead 2–0.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] The Athletics scored six runs in the first four innings to put the game out of reach.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] Mickey Cochrane's two-out home run in the first gave the A's their first run.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] After Al Simmons singled, Jimmie Foxx's RBI double made it 2–0 A's.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] George Watkins's home run in the second gave the Cardinals their only run of the game.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] In the third, Cochrane reached on an error and scored on Simmons's double.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] After an intentional walk, Bing Miller's RBI single made it 4–1 A's.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] Philadelphia added two more runs next inning on Jimmy Dykes's double.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] After the A's loaded the bases in the top of the first, Hallahan settled down and pitched a shutout.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] Philadelphia left a total of 11 men on base.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] The Cardinals scored the game's first run on Taylor Douthit's home run in the fourth, then next inning hit three consecutive one-out singles, the last of which by Charlie Gelbert scoring a run.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] In the seventh, Bill Shores allowed three consecutive leadoff singles, the last of which by Jimmie Wilson scoring two runs.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] Next inning, the Cardinals added another run off of Jack Quinn on back-to-back one-out doubles by Jim Bottomley and Chick Hafey.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] An error by Jimmy Dykes in the fourth inning allowed the Cardinals to score two runs.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] Haines did not allow a hit after the third inning.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] The A's got on the board in the first on Al Simmons's RBI single, but the Cardinals tied the game in the third when Charlie Gelbert tripled and scored on Jesse Haines's single.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] In the fourth, Chick Hafey hit a two-out ground rule double and scored on Dykes's error on Ray Blades's ground ball.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] Blades then scored on Gelbert's RBI single.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] George Earnshaw dueled Burleigh Grimes scoreless through seven innings before Lefty Grove took over for Earnshaw in the eighth.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] In the top of the ninth, Grimes walked Mickey Cochrane and then coughed up a home run ball to Jimmie Foxx.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] Earnshaw earned his second win on just one day of rest, pitching a five-hitter; it would be 88 years before another pitcher would start consecutive games in the postseason.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] Just like in Game 1, the A's seven hits came in five different innings, leading to two runs in the first and fourth innings, and single runs in the third, fifth, and sixth innings.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] As in Game 1, all the A's hits were extra-base hits, including home runs by Al Simmons and Jimmy Dykes.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] Although the A's hit only .197 (35–for–178) in the six game set, 18 of their hits went for extra bases, outscoring the Cardinals, 21–12.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] Louis only managed a .200 batting average in the series.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] The A's struck first in the first on RBI doubles by Mickey Cochrane and Bing Miller, both after walks.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] Simmon's home run in the third off of Syl Johnson made it 3–0 A's, then Dykes's home run after a walk in the fourth increased their lead to 5–0.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] The A's added to their lead next inning when Jimmie Foxx hit a leadoff double, moved to third on a bunt groundout and scored on Mule Haas's sacrifice fly. the A's scored their last run of the game in the sixth off of Jim Lindsey on Cochrane's sacrifice fly.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1930-world-series] The Cardinals scored their only run of the game on Chick Hafey's RBI double in the ninth.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] The **1931 World Series** featured the two-time defending champion Philadelphia Athletics and the St.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] The Cardinals beat the Athletics in seven games, a rematch and reversal of fortunes of the previous World Series.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] The same two teams faced off during the 1930 World Series and the Athletics were victorious.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] The only day-to-day player in the Cardinals' lineup who was different in 1931 was the "Wild Horse of the Osage", Pepper Martin—a 27-year-old rookie who had spent seven seasons in the minor leagues.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] He led his team for the Series in runs scored, hits, doubles, runs batted in and stolen bases, and also made a running catch to stifle a ninth-inning rally by the A's in the final game.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] The spitball pitch had been banned by Major League Baseball in 1920, but those still using it at that time were "grandfathered", or permitted to keep throwing it for the balance of their big-league careers.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] One of those who "wet his pill" still active in 1931 was Burleigh Grimes, with two Series starts, two wins and seven innings of no-hit pitching in Game 3.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] "Wild" Bill Hallahan started and won the other two for the Cards, and saved Game 7.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] The Athletics had captured their third straight American League pennant, winning 107 games (and 313 from 1929–31).
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] But this would prove to be the final World Series for longtime A's manager Connie Mack.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] As he did after the Boston "Miracle Braves" swept his heavily favored A's in the 1914 Series, Mack would break up this great team by selling off his best players, this time out of perceived economic necessity rather than pique and competition from the short-lived Federal League.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] It would be the A's last World Series appearance in Philadelphia and it would be 41 years—and two cities—later before the A's would return to the Fall Classic, after their successive moves to Kansas City in 1955 and Oakland in 1968.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] This would also be the city of Philadelphia's last appearance in the Series until 1950, and as of 2023 the only Series involving a Philadelphia team to last seven games.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] It was also the last World Series until the 2017 edition in which both teams who had won at least 100 games in the regular season went the maximum seven games.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] This was the first World Series to feature a team with numbers on the back of the uniform (Philadelphia).
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] The A's scored four runs in the third, enabling Lefty Grove to win Game 1 despite giving up 12 hits, three by Pepper Martin.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] The Cardinals struck first in the first inning on three consecutive one-out singles, the last of which to Jim Bottomley scoring a run.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] After a strikeout, Martin's double scored another run.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] In the top of the third with runners on first and second, Mule Haas's double scored Philadelphia's first run.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] Two consecutive walks by Paul Derringer loaded the bases and tied the game, then Jimmie Foxx's single scored two more runs.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] In the top of the seventh, Al Simmons's two-run home run put Philadelphia up 6–2, the game's final.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] Pepper Martin's two hits and two stolen bases, scoring both Cardinal runs, supported Hallahan's three-hit shutout.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] Grimes pitched a two-hitter and contributed a two-run single in the fourth.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] He had a shutout until Al Simmons hit a two-run homer with two outs in the ninth.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] Louis struck first in the second when with runners on first and third via a walk and single, Jimmie Wilson's single and Charlie Gelbert's lineout scored a run each.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] They added to their lead in the fourth off Lefty Grove on Burleigh Grimes's two-run single with runners on second and third, and added another run in the ninth off Roy Mahaffey on Jim Bottomley's double.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] George Earnshaw pitched a brilliant two-hit shutout, walking one and striking out eight.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] Simmons RBI double in the first inning after a walk and two groundouts was all Earnshaw needed.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] Philadelphia added to their lead in the sixth off Syl Johnson on Jimmie Foxx's home run and Jimmy Dykes's single after a Bing Miller double.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] Martin was a thorn in the A's side in the series, getting three hits and four RBI to lead St.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] Through five games, Martin leads all regulars with a .667 (12-18) average.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] Louis struck first in the first on Pepper Martin's sacrifice fly with runners on second and third.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] Martin's home run after a double in the sixth made it 3–0 Cardinals.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] The A's scored their only run in the seventh on Bing Miller's groundout after two one-out singles.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] The Cardinals added to their lead in the eighth when George Watkins walked off Rube Walberg, stole second and scored on Martin's single and in the ninth off Eddie Rommel on Charlie Gelbert's single with two on.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] The Athletics broke a scoreless tie with four runs in the fifth, Grove winning his second game of the series with a five-hitter, tying the series.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] After an error and walk off Paul Derringer, Dib Williams's RBI single scored the game's first run.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] Two two-out walks loaded the bases and scored another run.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] Mickey Cochrane's RBI single scored a run, then a walk to Al Simmons scored another.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] Louis scored their only run in the sixth when Jake Flowers doubled and scored on Frankie Frisch's single.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] The A's added to their lead in the seventh off Jim Lindsey.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] Max Bishop hit a leadoff single, moved to second on a bunt groundout, and scored on Al Simmons's single.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] After a single and hit-by-pitch loaded the bases, a walk to Jimmy Dykes scored a run and an error by Chick Hafey scored two more.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] The Cardinals struck first in the first when with runners on second and third via two single and a bunt groundout, a wild pitch by George Earnshaw to Pepper Martin scored a run and a strike three wild pitch to Ernie Orsatti scored another.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] A two-run home run by George Watkins in the third gave the Cardinals a 4-0 lead, but the Athletics scored two in the ninth on Doc Cramer's bases loaded two-run single, Hallahan getting the last out, saving the victory for Grimes.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] Despite going 0–for–6 in Games 6 and 7, Pepper Martin was the leading hitter of the series with a .500 (12–for–24) batting average.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] This was the Athletics’ final postseason appearance during their time in Philadelphia.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] The team failed to win a pennant during their time in Kansas City.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] The Athletics would have to wait until the move to Oakland, California for their next postseason appearance, which came in 1971, where they were swept by the Baltimore Orioles in the ALCS.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] The Athletics would eventually win the World Series again in 1972 over the Cincinnati Reds in seven games, which marked the start of a dynasty for the team.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1931-world-series] The Cardinals would return to the World Series three years later, where they defeated the Detroit Tigers in seven games for their third championship.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] The **1932 World Series** was the championship series in Major League Baseball for the 1932 season.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] The 29th edition of the World Series, it matched the American League (AL) champion New York Yankees versus the National League (NL) champions Chicago Cubs.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] By far it is mostly noteworthy for Babe Ruth's "called shot" home run, in his 10th and last World Series.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] It was punctuated by fiery arguments between the two teams, heating up the atmosphere before the World Series even began.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] A record 13 future Hall of Famers played in this World Series, with three other future Hall of Famers also participating: umpire Bill Klem, Yankees manager Joe McCarthy, and Cubs manager Rogers Hornsby.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] It was also the first World Series in which both teams wore uniforms with numbers on the backs of the shirts.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] In the sixth inning, they loaded the bases on three walks with one out before a two-run single by Bill Dickey and RBI fielder's choice by Ben Chapman knocked Bush out of the game.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] Burleigh Grimes in relief allowed two-out two-run single to Combs.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] The Cubs scored two in the seventh on Stephenson's two-run single, but in the bottom half, after a walk and single, Tony Lazzeri's RBI single, Chapman's sacrifice fly, and Grimes's wild pitch put the Yankees up 11–4.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] In the eighth, Gabby Hartnett hit a leadoff double and scored on Mark Koenig's triple.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] Billy Herman's groundout scored the Cubs' last run.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] The Yankees got one more run in the bottom half off Bob Smith when Combs doubled and scored on Joe Sewell's single.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] Yankee starter Red Ruffing pitched a complete game, striking out 10 Cubs but walking six and giving up six runs, only three of which were earned.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] In Game 2, Chicago scored first in the top of the first on Riggs Stephenson's sacrifice fly with runners on first and third off Lefty Gomez, but in the bottom half, after two leadoff walks, RBI singles by Lou Gehrig and Bill Dickey off Lon Warneke put the Yankees up 2–1.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] The Cubs tied the game in the third when Stephenson doubled with two outs and scored on Frank Demaree's single, but in the bottom half, Ben Chapman's two-run bases-loaded single put the Yankees ahead 4–2.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] They added another run in the fifth when Lou Gehrig hit a leadoff single, moved to second on a groundout and scored on Bill Dickey's single.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] This was the last World Series game Babe Ruth ever played in Yankee Stadium, with a single in his last Fall Classic home at-bat.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] Roughly 50,000 Cubs fans showed up for Game 3, a very large crowd for the time made possible by the construction of temporary bleachers fronting Waveland and Sheffield Avenues.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] In a prelude of things to come, Ruth and Gehrig put on an impressive batting display in batting practice.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] Ruth launched nine balls into the outfield stands, while Gehrig hit seven.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] As reported in the first edition of *A Day at the Park*, by William Hartel, p.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] Cub starter Charlie Root struggled in the opening frame.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] The first two Yankees reached base on a walk and error, and Babe Ruth followed with a home run into the right-center-field bleachers to put the Yanks up 3–0.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] The existing newsreel footage showed Gehrig giving Ruth a friendly swat on the buttocks as Ruth crossed the plate.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] Before their part of the first inning was over, the Yankees got two, two-out singles, but they failed to score any further runs in the inning.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] In the bottom half, Billy Herman drew a leadoff walk off George Pipgras and scored on Kiki Cuyler's double.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] Gehrig hit a home run in the top of the third to put the Yankees up 4–1.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] In the bottom half, Cuyler homered with one out, then after a single and forceout, Grimm's RBI double cut the Yankees lead to 4–3.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] Next inning, Billy Jurges doubled to left after Ruth's futile dive for the ball and scored on an error to tie the game.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] In the top of the fifth, Ruth came up to bat and, after making a series of pointing gestures, eventually hit a home run to centerfield, giving the Yankees the lead and control of the rest of the World Series.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] The home run, deemed Babe Ruth's called shot, has since become arguably the most iconic home run in baseball history.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] Many believe Ruth's pointing gestures to have been his declaring he would hit a home run to a specific point in the stands, although evidence has suggested that he was actually pointing his finger tauntingly at the Cubs' dugout.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] Root would only throw one more pitch, which Gehrig hit for a back-to-back home run, putting the Yankees up 6–4 and knocking Root out of the game.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] The Yankees got another run in the ninth aided by two errors on Champman's double off Jakie May.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] Though Gabby Hartnett hit a leadoff home run in the bottom half and Billy Jurges singled off Pipgras, Herb Pennock retired the next three batters to end the game and leave the Yankees one win away from the championship.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] The Yankees loaded the bases in the top of the first on two singles and a hit-by-pitch, but scored just once on Lou Gehrig's sacrifice fly.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] A walk loaded the bases, but Lon Warneke in relief of Guy Bush retired the next two batters to end the inning.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] In the bottom half, after two singles, Frank Demaree's three-run home run off Johnny Allen put the Cubs atop 3–1.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] After an error and single, Billy Jurges's RBI single knocked Allen out of the game.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] Wilcy Moore relieved him and put the fire out, giving up only one additional run in 5+1⁄3 innings.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] Tony Lazzeri's two-out two-run home run in the third cut the Cubs' lead to 4–3.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] The Yankees took the lead in the sixth on a two-run single by Gehrig off Jakie May, but in the bottom half, two errors allowed the Cubs to tie the game.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] In the seventh, after loading the bases, three straight hits by Earle Combs, Joe Sewell and the Babe, the last World Series hits for Sewell and Ruth, put the Yankees up for good, 9–5.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] A hit-by-pitch reloaded the bases, but Bud Tinning retired two to end the inning.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] The Yankees blew the game open in the ninth off Burleigh Grimes, starting with a leadoff home run by Earle Combs, then after two outs, Gehrig walked before Lazzeri's second home run of the game made it 12–5 Yankees.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] They scored one more run when Bill Dickey singled and scored on Ben Chapman's double.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] In the bottom half, Herb Pennock allowed a leadoff single to Billy Herman who stole second and third on defensive indifferences and scored on Woody English's groundout before Pennock retired the next two hitters to end the series.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] The Yankees had won their fourth World Series, and their 12th consecutive Series game.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] It was the last Series for Yankee mainstays Ruth, Combs and Pennock.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] The Cubs extended their World Series victory drought to 24 years with their humiliating loss, their fourth consecutive in the Fall Classic after 1910, 1918 and 1929 (to the A's, Red Sox and A's again respectively).
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] The Cubs' drought would end up lasting 108 years, having been finally ended when the Cubs defeated the Cleveland Indians in seven games to win the 2016 World Series.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] Despite Ruth's heroics, Gehrig was the real hero of the series batting .529 (he collected 9 hits out of 17 times at bat) with 8 RBIs and 3 home runs.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] Bench jockeying, called "trash talk" nowadays, was standard procedure in baseball then as now.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] Despite Koenig's regular-season contributions (hitting .353 and fielding well), his stingy Cub teammates voted him only half a player's postseason share before the start of the Series because he had only played in 33 games and was unable to play in the Series due to injury.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] When some of Koenig's Yankee friends got wind of this, they dissed the Cubs as "cheapskates" in the press, "tight" with their Series money.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] Ruth infuriated the Cubs the most when he called them cheapskates.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] Adding spice to the verbal stew was that Yankee manager Joe McCarthy had been fired by the Cubs a year or two after leading them to the 1929 NL pennant.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] When the Series started in New York, the Cubs retaliated by calling the Babe "fat" and "washed up" along with every obscenity they could think of.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1932-world-series] Guy Bush, Cub starter in Game 1, led the verbal attack on Ruth, calling him "nigger" (a common bench-jockey slam against the Babe for his broad nose and thick lips despite his German origin), and banter like this went on for most of the Series.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The **1933 Major League Baseball All-Star Game** was the first edition of the All-Star Game known as the "Midsummer Classic".
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] This was the first official playing of the midseason exhibition baseball game between Major League Baseball's (MLB's) National League (NL) and American League (AL) All-Star teams.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game was held on July 6, 1933, at Comiskey Park in Chicago, Illinois, the home of the AL's Chicago White Sox.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game resulted in the AL defeating the NL, 4–2, in two hours and five minutes.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The first official All-Star Game came 22 years after the Addie Joss Benefit Game of July 24, 1911, when the American League's Cleveland Naps faced a team of all-stars from other American League teams at League Park in Cleveland, Ohio; the game was won by the all-star squad, 5–3.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The first official MLB All-Star exhibition game on July 6, 1933, was held at Comiskey Park (1910–1990) and was part of the 1933 Chicago World's Fair during the city's centennial.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The 1933 MLB All-Star Game was the idea of Arch Ward, the sports editor of the *Chicago Tribune*, after the Mayor of Chicago, Edward J.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Kelly, had first approached the *Tribune's* publisher for a major sport event.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game was intended to be a one-time event to boost morale during the Great Depression.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Ward decided that the fans would select the starting nine players and the managers the other nine players for each of the NL and AL All-Star teams.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The *Tribune* called it the "Game of the Century", and 55 newspapers across the country printed the fans' ballots in their papers.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The *Tribune* estimated the game's attendance on July 6, 1933, at 49,000.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The proceeds ($45,000, net gate receipts) from the game went to a charity for disabled and needy major league players.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The All-Star Game would afterwards be known as MLB's "Midsummer Classic".
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The legendary Babe Ruth of the Yankees highlighted the game by hitting a two-run home run to right field in the bottom of the third inning and catching a fly ball up against the scoreboard in right-center field in the top of the eighth inning.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Ruth was greeted at home plate by the AL/Chicago White Sox batboy John McBride and teammate Lou Gehrig.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Twenty of the game's thirty-six All-Stars including Ruth would later be inducted into the National Baseball Hall of Fame at Cooperstown, New York.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Both the game's managers, five out of six coaches, and two out of the four umpires on the field that day would also be future Hall of Famers.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Two AL All-Stars were White Sox players, starting third baseman Jimmy Dykes and starting center fielder Al Simmons.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Yankee Lefty Gomez was the winning pitcher for the American League.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The NL team wore specially made gray uniforms and navy blue caps with "National League" in navy blue felt letters on the front of the jersey, a large navy blue felt number on the back and "NL" in white letters printed on the navy caps.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The AL team members each wore their home uniform.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The NL members were allowed to keep their All-Star uniforms and caps.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] In 1934, each NL member used their home uniform and cap.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game's official AL baseball was changed to an official NL baseball and the AL home plate umpire was replaced by a NL home plate umpire after the top of the 5th inning.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] 60 baseballs autographed by All-Star players were given out before the game started.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Personnel in *italics* have since been inducted into the National Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The umpires rotated positions clockwise in the middle of the fifth inning, with Klem moving behind the plate.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Chick Hafey of the National League had the first hit, a bloop single to center field to lead off the second inning.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The American League got on the board first in the bottom of the second.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] NL pitcher Bill Hallahan issued one-out walks to Jimmy Dykes and Joe Cronin.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Two batters later, the game's winning pitcher Lefty Gomez, singled home Dykes for the AL's first run.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] In the bottom of the third, after a walk to Charlie Gehringer, Babe Ruth famously hit the first home run in All-Star Game history, putting the AL up 3–0.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Hallahan was chased from the game after walking Lou Gehrig immediately afterward, and was replaced by Lon Warneke.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] General Crowder replaced Gomez to start the fourth inning.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] In the sixth, Warneke hit a one-out triple and scored on a Pepper Martin groundout.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Frankie Frisch followed with a home run to bring the NL to within a run, but after a Chuck Klein single, Crowder would escape the inning without giving up any more damage.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Cronin led off the bottom of the sixth with a single.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] After advancing on a bunt, he scored on an Earl Averill single to extend the lead to 4–2.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Crowder would be replaced by Lefty Grove in the top of the seventh, while Warneke was replaced by Carl Hubbell in the bottom of the inning.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The NL looked to have a chance in the top of the eighth.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] With Frisch on first with two outs, Hafey lined a shot to right field that looked like it could be a home run, but Ruth reached over the wall to catch it, denying the NL a chance to tie the game.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1933-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Grove retired the side in order in the ninth to secure the American League's victory.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The **1941 Major League Baseball All-Star Game** was the ninth playing of the mid-summer classic between the all-stars of the American League (AL) and National League (NL), the two leagues comprising Major League Baseball.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The game was held on July 8, 1941, at Briggs Stadium in Detroit, Michigan, the home of the Detroit Tigers of the American League.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The American League defeated the National League, 7–5.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] With the NL leading 5–4, two outs in the bottom of the ninth inning, and Joe Gordon and Joe DiMaggio of the New York Yankees on base; Ted Williams of the Boston Red Sox hit a walk-off home run off of Claude Passeau of the Chicago Cubs to win it for the AL.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Prior to Williams' at-bat DiMaggio hit a potential game-ending double play groundball.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] However, Billy Herman’s relay throw pulled first baseman Frank McCormick off the bag, thus extending the game and setting up Williams' at-bat.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] In the end, the AL's dramatic 7–5 walk-off win overshadowed two home runs hit by Pittsburgh Pirates shortstop Arky Vaughan, which had given the NL 3–2 and 5–2 leads in the seventh and eighth innings, respectively.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Players in *italics* have since been inducted into the National Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The umpires changed assignments in the middle of the fifth inning – Summers and Pinelli swapped positions, also Jorda and Grieve swapped positions.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Bob Feller (Cleveland, AL) and Whit Wyatt (Brooklyn, NL) pitched three and two scoreless innings, respectively, to start the game.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Neither team put a runner in scoring position until the fourth inning, when doubles by Cecil Travis (Washington) and Ted Williams off Paul Derringer (Cincinnati) put the AL ahead 1–0.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Bucky Waters (Cincinnati) led off the sixth inning with a double.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] A bunt by Stan Hack (Chicago Cubs) moved Waters to third and a sacrifice fly by Terry Moore (St.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The AL answered in the bottom half of the same inning when Cleveland shortstop Lou Boudreau (who had entered the game for Joe Cronin) singled home Joe DiMaggio for a 2–1 AL lead.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The top halves of the seventh and eighth innings saw the heroics of Arky Vaughan, who hit a two-run home run in each to also score two St.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Louis Cardinals players: Enos Slaughter, who had opened the seventh inning with a single, and Johnny Mize, who had preceded Vaughan's round-tripper in the eighth with a one-out double.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] With the score now 5–2 in favor of the National League the first pair of brothers to ever appear together in an All-Star Game cut into the NL lead, when Dom DiMaggio – in his first plate appearance of the game – singled home Joe after his one-out double.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] In the ninth inning, White Sox pitcher Eddie Smith, who had given up one of Vaughan's home runs, retired the NL in order in his second inning of work.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] One of the three NL hitters to step to the plate that half-inning was pitcher Claude Passeau, who – with his team leading 5–3 – was not pulled for a pinch hitter, and thus returned to the mound in the bottom of the ninth for his third inning of work.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] With one out in the bottom of the ninth, three consecutive AL batters reached base, putting the tying and go-ahead runs on base and bringing Joe DiMaggio to the plate.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The “Yankee Clipper” then hit what some sources describe as a routine double-play groundball, which would have ended the ballgame.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] However, the relay throw from second to first by Billy Herman pulled first baseman Frank McCormick off the bag and extended the game.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] With the NL still leading 5–4 (a run had scored on DiMaggio's groundout), the AL now had the tying run on third and the winning run on first.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Not electing to walk Ted Williams, which would have advanced the winning run to second base and brought Dom DiMaggio to the plate, NL manager Bill McKechnie let Passeau pitch to Williams.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] With the count two balls and one strike Williams hit a three-run home run off the third deck of the right field stands of Detroit's Briggs Stadium for a 7–5 American League victory.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The 1941 All-Star Game took place in the midst of Joe DiMaggio’s 56-game hitting streak (but did not count towards it, as the All-Star Game is regarded as an exhibition game).
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] DiMaggio had equaled the all-time record of 44 games, set by Willie Keeler in 1897, seven days prior to the All-Star Game and broken it the day after that (July 1 and 2, respectively).
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The streak would end nine days after the All-Star Game, when DiMaggio went hitless on July 17 against the Cleveland Indians.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Ted Williams, whose batting average was at .405 at the time of the All-Star Game, would even slightly improve on that hitting pace for the rest of the season and end the 1941 campaign at .406, making him the last hitter to reach the .400 mark for a season.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The 1941 Major League Baseball season, of which the All-Star Game marked the midway point, was the last played prior to the United States' entry into World War II.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] The juxtaposition of that memorable season taking place with the war looming is illustrated in the 1991 book *Baseball in ’41* by renowned sportswriter Robert Creamer.
[src:1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game/1941-major-league-baseball-all-star-game] Although the Major League season and the World Series would continue to be played during the war years, the All-Star Game was cancelled in 1945 due to wartime travel restrictions.
